World Box seemed like a harmless game when I first stumbled upon it. A virtual sandbox where I could create my own worlds, shape destinies, and escape the mundanity of reality. Little did I know that the captivating allure of World Box would unravel the fabric of my family, leaving me with a haunting emptiness that no virtual realm could fill.

As the days turned into weeks and the weeks into months, World Box became more than just a game; it became an addiction. The vibrant laughter that once echoed through our home was replaced by the deafening silence of a father engrossed in his virtual sanctuary. My wife, Sarah, and our children, Emily and Michael, began to fade into the background as I delved deeper into the pixelated landscapes I meticulously crafted.

At first, I dismissed their concerns, attributing my newfound passion to stress relief and the need for a temporary escape. However, as the world within the screen became my reality, the lines between the two blurred, and I failed to see the toll it was taking on my family. The bedtime stories, weekend outings, and cherished family traditions became relics of the past as World Box consumed my every waking moment.

Sarah's pleas for connection fell on deaf ears, and the once-strong bonds within our family eroded like sand slipping through my virtual fingertips. One day, as I was lost in the intricacies of my digital creations, I realized the depth of my negligence. Sarah had made the heart-wrenching decision to leave, taking Emily and Michael with her.

The game that once promised an escape became the catalyst for my isolation, tearing apart the very foundation of my family. World Box had granted me control over fictional realms, but in the process, I lost the most precious world of all – the one within the walls of my own home.

But Other Than That

I liked this game and that's all I have to say about it, but I'd like to address the arguments of people who don't like this game.
 The main argument is that game does not have enough content for what the price is. I say, for one, most people who leave negative reviews don't play for more than 7 hours and sometimes near 24, while people who leave a positive review have played for 6, 10, 19, or 200 hours. The people who leave bad reviews should play the game more to actually see everything a few times so an accurate judgement, I know about the 2 hour refund period but your review is more valid if you play longer, and it's still in early access, you getting this game is to give constructive criticism, say what features you'ed like to be in the game, and not say it needs more content when you could help it get more content for your and others enjoyment.

DO NOT LET THE AESTHETICS FOOL YOU - Worldbox is every bit simulation, DESPITE what it's cute 'n fuzzy pixelated graphics might have you believe. Worldbox isn't messing around when it calls itself a god simulator, because you can be as hands-on or hands-off as you please with this game.  I ran this one for two days straight in the background, only to find the world I left with an assortment of races became dominated by elves waging their own world war. Whilst playing hands-on, can easily feel like messing around with disasters in SimCity. But the most satisfying experience comes from allowing you're world's denizens the freedom to explore their own free will and seeing the world they create for themselves.
Speaking of denizens...  You have Humans, Elves, Dwarves and Orks to choose from as well all manner or animals to choose from, along with a host of supernatural menaces to indirectly spice things up.  Otherwise, you can roll up those godly sleeves unleashing blessings, curses and a craptonne of plagues to choose from...  Should you feel the need to indulge in such things.
Whether you're playing this on Steam, Android or iOS you're going to get you money's worth real fast especially if you're into god games! Worldbox is definitely a nice addition for lovers of simulations.

The most addictive and innovative game I've played in years.
This game allows you too seamlessly weave large-scale and intricate stories within your own customized fantasy universe. From crafting sprawling civilizations to causing wars and cataclysmic events, every option at your disposal is fun and empowering. 
What truly sets this game apart is the dynamic world simulation. You can watch the evolution and sprawl of civilizations, observe their interactions, and even intervene however you feel necessary. Striving to create a peaceful coexistence or simply introducing more chaos, the game's NPCs respond organically to your actions, making every single playthrough unique.

World Box - God Simulator offers a captivating and unique experience in the god simulation genre. With impressive creative freedom, players can shape worlds from early stages to advanced civilizations. The simple interface balances perfectly with the complexity of interactions, making the game accessible. Pixelated graphics and a charming soundtrack add a special charm, while the unpredictability of events keeps gameplay fresh. An epic journey of creation and discovery, providing hours of creative fun and unexpected surprises. Enthusiastically recommended for simulation enthusiasts seeking a distinctive experience.

Advices:

1- The map is too narrow, it should be expanded.
2- The number of living things is low, it should be increased.
3- We cannot intervene in the events that occur automatically over the ages in the game. Since it's God Simulator, we should be able to. If I want, I should be able to stop the acid rain that starts at that moment.
4- When I click on the individuals of the races, there should be an option where I can kill them if I want or fill their health bars.
5- The shapes and sizes of the icons we use when creating the world are very inadequate. These should also be expanded along with Maple.

I am especially in favor of increasing the number of races and creatures and expanding the map. However, the limits of freedom should also be expanded. These are the features I have noticed so far that can increase the playability of the game for longer hours. After spending some more time with the game, I'll add it if there's something that catches my attention.

Tavsiyeler: 

1- Map çok dar, genişletilmeli.
2- Canlı sayısı az, artırılmalı. 
3- Oyunda, çağlarda otomatik olarak gelişen olaylara müdahale edemiyoruz. Madem God Simulator, edebilmeliyiz. Canım isterse o an başlayan asit yağmurunu durdurabilmeliyim. 
4- Irkların bireylerinin üzerine tıkladığımda, onları istersem öldürebileceğim istersem can barlarını doldurabileceğim bir seçenek olmalı. 
5- Dünya yaratırken kullandığımız ikonların şekilleri ve boyutları çok yetersiz. Maple birlikte bunlar da genişletilmeli. 

Özellikle ırk ve canlı sayısının artırılması, haritanın genişletilmesi taraftarıyım. Bununla birlikte özgürlüklerin sınırı da genişletilmeli. Bunlar şu ana dek farkettiğim, oyunun daha uzun saatler oynanabilirliğini artırabilecek özellikler. Oyunda biraz daha vakit geçirdikten sonra dikkatimi çeken bir şeyler olursa eklerim.

It's a neat little game but there are three issues that bother me to the point where I just can't recommend it.

1 - Map sizes are pitifully small. Even at max map size, a moderately big town will cover like 20% of the whole world.
2 - You can (re)name everything in the game - except the changed names don't show up in your world's history books. This kinda defeats the purpose of both features.
3 - $20 price tag is just too steep.

Will change my review if this changes but for now with a heavy heart, it's a no.

I have to say. This is one of the best GOD games out there. I'm actually enjoying it even though the graphics are crap. Very enjoyable and able to Create my own content while watching the world advance. My will shall be done, here on earth as it is in heaven. I enjoy watching them expand and tackle any challenge I throw at them. I enjoy trying to start an zombie Apocalypse which changes the balance of world power. I like how the ruins of the previous civilization is left behind waiting to be tear down by other civilizations or new ones. The ruins of old civilization actually is one of the best features. I like seeing other civilizations move in and build around them or knock them down to make room to build. One of the statue was left standing from the previous human kingdom that ruled over the entire planet before the orcs took over. I allowed humanity to rule all over earth and advance in peace covering the entire globe. Then they fell from the plague, rebellions, and zombies. Orcs moved in with what ever that was left of humanity. Nothing but ancient human ruins all across the globe. I just added the elves. The Human Civilization is coming to an end from greed and power. They need to redeem themselves to me their god lol.

Update: weeeelllll Never mind on them proving themselves to me. As I was writing the review, the orks wiped out what was left  of them. they were on this island isolated from the main land. I didn't know the game doesn't pause when hitting the window key to get to the desktop screen lol. The only thing left of the human civilization are the ruins and marvelous statues.

Some things I don't like. One of them is the advancement stops at medieval era. Nothing else beyond that. I don't like the fact that there is no fog of war. Everybody already knows where everybody is at. Battles happens to quickly to where it feels like its on fast mode. There is no identification on the advancement progress of each civilization. I don't like the size of the map. Seems too small. I would like to add more civs and expand the world.Everything is too close.

Overall, I like the game and is enjoyable. I hope they add a lot more content and expand the map.

Hello, I am fernbyfilms@gmail.com. And I am reviewing this game, Worldbox. Pretty much, if you want a game that has unlimited options to play with it, this is it. The game is a Pixel Game though being very well entertaining, through recent updates, I would say it gets updates of about 1 update per 3 months. Or more depending on the people who have played for a longer period of time than I have, this game also runs very smoothly (depending on the PC you have) and will be a very good play if you have some time to cut. This game also lets you play with a ton of animals and mythological creatures. From sea turtles to dragons you have very good options with what you want to play with. But this game does also have some spice to it.

Humans, Elves, Orcs, and Dwarves, very good. They are the only species that can populate and have cities, and you can get me started on the Ages/Eras, the Ages are very well done, there is a total of 10 Ages/Eras. Age of: Hope, Sun, Dark, Tears, Moon, Chaos, Enchantment, Ice, Ash, and Despair. But, Mods... Mods in particular (the unofficial editing of a game which you can download onto the main game) are very hard to get, they get completely wiped from little kids because you need discord. And discord needs to verify your age to see if you are at least 16+, so this terminates Mods for the little kids who play the game... But I would like to make my final verdict before this review turns into a whole document.

Its a Pixel Game, different and unique options to play, different sets of Age/Eras, Fictional Game. My Final Verdict: HIGHLY RECOMMENDED. I see no reason why you won't purchase this game.

It's always a good day when you get a God-Sim that doesn't force you to be a benevolent and helping God, but actually lets you be god with all his facets, be it good or bad.

The core gameplay loop is simple: you create a world to your liking with different biomes, resources, dangers, animals or evil wizards. Where you place and create islands, continents or volcanoes is entirely up to you. After you have completed your world, you can unleash up to 4 different races on it (orcs, humans, elves and dwarves), who will immediately start building settlements, harvesting resources and taking care of dangers (if they'll survive whatever the world had in store for them).

From here on it's mostly just watch and wait as civilizations will develop over time, research technologies, plunder, expand, found religions or rebel against the king and secede. In the end, you don't have to participate as a god unless you want to help a group or simply use your destructive powers to bring death and chaos to the world.

All in all, a good game to simply relax and observe. Unfortunately the workshop support is only for maps so far, I hope we get some decent official mod support.

If you're looking for a review on this game you've come to the wrong place, but if you're looking for an outstanding pie recipe you've come to the right place.

Ingredients:

1. 6 tablespoons unsalted butter
2. 1/2 cup white sugar
3. 1/2 cup brown sugar
4. 1/4 cup water
5. 1/4 teaspoon cinnamon
6. 1 pinch salt
7. 5 apples - peeled, cored and sliced
8. 1 pastry for double-crust pie

Directions:

1. Preheat oven to 425 degrees F (220 degrees C).
2. Combine butter, white sugar, brown sugar, water, cinnamon, and salt in a saucepan over medium heat. Bring to a boil, remove from heat and set aside.
3. Roll out half the pastry to fit a 9-inch pie plate. Place bottom crust in pie plate; pour in apple slices.
4. Roll out top crust into a 10-inch circle. Cut into 8 (1-inch) wide strips with a sharp paring knife or pastry wheel. Weave the pastry strips, one at a time, into a lattice pattern. Fold the ends of the lattice strips under the edge of the bottom crust and crimp to seal.
5. Pour butter-sugar mixture over top of pie, coating the lattice, and allowing any remaining sauce to drizzle through the crust.
6. Bake in the preheated oven for 15 minutes. Reduce heat to 350 degrees F (175 degrees C), and bake until the crust is golden brown, the caramel on the top crust is set, and the apple filling is bubbling, 35 to 40 more minutes. Allow to cool completely before slicing.

I 'punished' a kingdom for starting a war that killed off the last Orcs by blowing up their land and rebuilding it. I put a massive land border of mountains to separate it and put new Orcs there. That area became a safe haven for humans to bounce back (yes they killed the Orcs again) after a zombie apocalypse nearly killed off everyone on the continent (twice).

That zombie apocalypse started after punishing another kingdom for their part in killing off the Orcs, by uprooting them from their home island. So i plagued the island where they built one of their villages with Biomass, with a few zombies to help kill them off... only for one of the infected to escape onto mainland. After trying to fix my mistake shining divine light over every reach of the entire continent, I left humanity to fend for itself for the next 1400 years.

That kingdom, the Realm of the Sha, fended off zombies as the sole kingdom for 500 years, gradually claiming more land before a rebellion, the Realm of the Kos, split the kingdom into two. 200 years later, the Realm of the Kos would finish off the Sha, unwittingly triggering a wave of zombie infections which almost destroyed all life on the continent. The safe haven I built for humanity, which became a village with 3 town halls and a population of nearly 1000, was dismantled by the zombies.

Miraculously, after being whittled down to 160 villagers, they slowly began reclaiming the continent. By the 1500s, all other cultures were wiped out, and the Realm of the Kos repopulated the continent. By the 1800s, the zombie apocalypse had been completely wiped out, and humanity thrived again.

Review by Guts, the Black Swordsman

Worldbox, huh? I've battled demons, fought the God Hand, and even had my arm bitten off, but this... this is a whole new level of bizarre. Let's dive in and see if this world-building adventure can make me laugh harder than Griffith's so-called "dream."

The graphics are like a pixelated version of Griffith's dream – shiny, pretty, and completely detached from reality. It's like witnessing Griffith's ascension to godhood in 8-bit glory. Can we add a pixelated Behelit for some extra flair? No? Okay, moving on.

The controls are easier to master than trying to grasp the depths of Griffith's manipulative schemes. It's a point-and-click adventure that even a one-armed, one-eyed swordsman could handle. You'll feel like a real Hawk of Light, minus the hawk.

In Worldbox, you become the divine hand that shapes civilizations, like how Griffith shaped the Band of the Hawk. The difference is, you don't need to betray anyone to create your dream world here. So, be a better leader than Griffith, and maybe your flock won't hate you.

But wait, there's more! If you want to have some Berserk fun, try recreating the Eclipse event – with cute little pixelated Apostles and everything! Just remember, unlike Griffith, you don't have to sacrifice your comrades – you can actually be a decent overlord.

In conclusion, Worldbox is a quirky world-building game that lets you play creator instead of sacrificing your friends for your dream. So, get your virtual God Hand ready and shape a world even more surprising than Griffith's fall from grace. Just don't be tempted by any mysterious Behelits along the way!

Worldbox - God Simulator: A Sandbox of Divine Creativity

Worldbox, the God Simulator, offers players the unique experience of wielding omnipotent powers to shape and influence a world of their own creation. Developed by Maxim Karpenko, this indie gem provides a sandbox for players to unleash their inner deity and craft their own epic narratives. In this in-depth review, we'll delve into the various aspects that make Worldbox an enchanting and captivating god game.

Graphics and Art Style (8/10):
Worldbox boasts a pixel art style that, while minimalistic, is surprisingly charming and expressive. The game's visuals, which might seem rudimentary at first glance, progressively reveal their intricate beauty as you delve into the game's mechanics and world-building capabilities. The aesthetic choice contributes to the game's unique character and allows the player's imagination to fill in the gaps, making the pixel art a perfect canvas for your divine creations.

Gameplay (9/10):
At its core, Worldbox is about divine intervention and the power to create, shape, and destroy. The game allows you to place and control various life forms, such as humans, animals, and mythological creatures, and influence their development. You can create a world teeming with civilizations, guiding their evolution from primitive tribes to advanced empires. The level of detail is astonishing, with factors like temperature, terrain, and the availability of resources playing a significant role in the growth of your creations.

The ability to customize your world is a key feature, letting you sculpt the land, set the weather, and even introduce magic into your domain. The freedom to create and experiment is vast, making each playthrough unique. This sandbox nature ensures that no two games are ever alike, and the game's replayability is a testament to its depth and complexity.

The AI-driven interactions between the inhabitants of your world add another layer of depth to the gameplay. Watching your citizens form societies, wage wars, and develop alliances is fascinating, as the world you've created takes on a life of its own.

Audio (7/10):
The sound design in Worldbox is simple but effective. The game's serene and atmospheric music complements the meditative nature of world-building, and the sound effects, while not overly impressive, do a decent job of immersing you in your divine realm. It's worth noting that sound design is not a primary focus of the game, and the simplicity of the audio serves to highlight the importance of the gameplay and creativity.

Replayability (10/10):
The true magic of Worldbox lies in its replayability. Every game session allows you to experiment with different scenarios, shaping the world in countless ways. Whether you prefer to be a benevolent deity, fostering peace and prosperity, or a malevolent force, sowing chaos and destruction, the game accommodates your choices. It's a testament to the game's depth that you can play for hours on end without ever growing tired of its possibilities.

Community and Mods (9/10):
Worldbox benefits greatly from a dedicated modding community, which continually expands the game's possibilities. There's a plethora of user-generated content available, from new creatures and buildings to gameplay tweaks and enhancements. This extends the game's life even further, as it's not just the developer but also the community that contributes to the evolution of the game.

Overall (9/10):
Worldbox - God Simulator is a creative masterpiece that taps into the desire to wield godlike powers and craft unique, evolving worlds. It's an engrossing and deeply satisfying experience, offering an impressive level of control over the destinies of your digital denizens. With its evolving features, mod support, and limitless replayability, Worldbox is a must-play for fans of sandbox and simulation games, as well as anyone who's ever wondered what it's like to be a divine creator. Dive in and let your godly imagination run wild in this pixelated universe.

One of the best god games I have ever played.  My experience with god games goes back to Black and White up to modern day Colony Sims and everything in between.  To me what makes a "God Game" is watching the little people go about their daily lives with names, homes, and needs.  These things make every event feel so much more personal as you watch these people survive events as one inevitably rises to rule the others as the others die along the way.  Worldbox understands this and has done a better job with it than almost any "God Game" has in the past ~15 years.  

So many updates later and this game has become really amazing.  A ton of different systems running together create a living world.  If you like God Games and tolerate/enjoy pixel graphics, you will really like this game.

I seriously don't like simulation games - usually I quickly run out of fun ideas to do and unless there is some actual goal, I don't see any reason to continue. So why tf is this one so addicting???

To answer my own question: The amount of dynamics in the civilizations makes looking at your created worlds like watching fish in an aquarium. They constantly grow, split up, fight each other, found new villages, destroy others, get hit by disasters... Involuntarily you become invested, in the story of a person, a city maybe, a country. Maybe a kingdom makes its last stand on a beautiful island and from that point on, this island will always have a place in your heart. Maybe a random dude manages to kill a fire wizard terrorizing the whole world and rises up to become king - or dies in the next orc attack. A war is turned because the overwhelmingly large aggressor has multiple revolutions which allows the Alliance of Light to rebuild and finally defend. Maybe the last dwarven village, one that has existed since the beginning of time, falls victim to the armies of the immortal elven overlord, ushering in a millenium of elven domination on that continent - ended only by the combined efforts of multiple human kingdoms, united against a common foe. 

All of these are just single sentences taken from stories that happened on one or the other world of mine - stories I will not forget for a long time and the reason why this game is so brilliant.

I started playing this game on mobile, but I wanted to be able to have larger worlds and mods so I switched. This game is worth the amount it costs since you can have hours of fun watching civilizations rise and fall over time. I also can't wait for the addition of new content that will make this amazing game even better.

"WorldBox" is a popular sandbox simulation game that allows players to create and shape their own virtual worlds. Its appeal and reasons for being considered a good game can vary from player to player, but here are some common reasons why many people enjoy "WorldBox":

Creativity and Freedom: "WorldBox" offers players a high degree of creative freedom. You can design and control your world, including its geography, weather, creatures, and civilizations. This creative aspect appeals to players who enjoy open-ended gameplay and want to express their imagination.

Simulation and Realism: The game's simulation mechanics, such as the realistic physics, weather systems, and population dynamics, make it interesting and engaging. Players can experiment with different scenarios and observe how their world evolves based on their actions.

Unique Emergent Gameplay: "WorldBox" is known for its emergent gameplay, where unexpected and unique events can occur based on the interactions between various elements in the game. This element of surprise and discovery keeps players engaged.

Modding Community: "WorldBox" has an active modding community that creates and shares custom content, including new creatures, biomes, and gameplay mechanics. This extends the game's longevity and allows players to customize their experience.

Relaxing and Meditative: Some players find "WorldBox" to be a relaxing and meditative experience. The slow-paced gameplay allows for thoughtful planning and design without the pressure of time limits or competition.

Updates and Development: The developers of "WorldBox" continue to release updates and improvements to the game, which keeps players interested and engaged over time. New features and bug fixes enhance the gameplay experience.

Community and Sharing: The game allows players to share their worlds and creations with others. This fosters a sense of community and encourages players to showcase their imaginative creations.

Multiplatform Availability: "WorldBox" is available on multiple platforms, including PC and mobile devices, making it accessible to a wide audience.

It's important to note that what makes a game "good" is highly subjective and can vary from person to person. While many players enjoy "WorldBox" for the reasons mentioned above, others may have different preferences and opinions. Ultimately, the enjoyment of a game depends on an individual's interests and gaming preferences.

IN the beginning God created the heaven and the earth.

And the earth was without form, and void; and darkness was upon the face of the deep. And the Spirit of God moved upon the face of the waters.

And God said, Let there be light: and there was light.

And God saw the light, that it was good: and God divided the light from the darkness.

And God called the light Day, and the darkness he called Night. And the evening and the morning were the first day.

And God said, Let there be a firmament in the midst of the waters, and let it divide the waters from the waters.

And God made the firmament, and divided the waters which were under the firmament from the waters which were above the firmament: and it was so.

And God called the firmament Heaven. And the evening and the morning were the second day.
And God said, Let the waters under the heaven be gathered together unto one place, and let the dry land appear: and it was so.

And God called the dry land Earth; and the gathering together of the waters called he Seas: and God saw that it was good.

And God said, Let the earth bring forth grass, the herb yielding seed, and the fruit tree yielding fruit after is kind, whose seed is in itself, upon the earth: and it was so.

And the earth brought forth grass, and herb yielding seed after his kind, and the tree yielding fruit, whose seed was in itself, after his kind: and God saw that it was good.

And the evening and the morning were the third day.

And God said, Let there be lights in the firmament of the heaven to divide the day from the night; and let them be for signs, and for seasons, and for days, and years:

And let them be for lights in the firmament of the heaven to give light upon the earth: and it was so.

And God made two great lights; the greater light to rule the day, and the lesser light to rule the night: he made the stars also.

And God set them in the firmament of the heaven to give light upon the earth.

And to rule over the day and over the night, and to divide the light from the darkness: and God saw that it was good.

And the evening and the morning were the fourth day.

And God said, Let the waters bring forth abundantly the moving creature that hath life, and fowl that may fly above the earth in the open firmament of heaven.

And God created great whales, and every living creature that moveth, which the waters brought forth abundantly, after their kind, and every winged fowl after his kind: and God saw that it was good.

And God blessed them, saying, Be fruitful, and multiply, and fill the waters in the seas, and let fowl multiply in the earth.

And the evening and the morning were the fifth day.

And God said, Let the earth bring forth the living creature after his kind, cattle, and creeping thing, and beast of the earth after his kind: and it was so.

And God made the beast of the earth after his kind, and cattle after their kind, and every thing that creepeth upon the earth after his kind: and God saw that it was good.

And God said, Let us make man in our image, after our likeness: and let them have dominion over the fish of the sea, and over the fowl of the air, and over the cattle, and over all the earth, and over every creeping thing that creepeth upon the earth.

So God created man in his own image, in the image of God created he him; male and female created he them.

And God blessed them, and God said unto them, Be fruitful, and multiply, and replenish the earth, and subdue it: and have dominion over the fish of the sea, and over the fowl of the air, and over every living thing that moveth upon the earth.

And God said, Behold, I have given you every herb bearing seed, which is the upon the face of all the earth, and every tree, in which is the fruit of a tree yielding seed; to you it shall be for meat.

And to every beast of the earth, and to every fowl of the air, and to every thing that creepeth upon the earth, wherein there is life, I have given every green herb for meat: and it was so.

And God saw every thing that he had made, and, behold, it was very good. And the evening and the morning were the sixth day.

I've played the game a lot, and personally I think it's great, especially as updates regularly add new content. The game has evolved enormously since its inception: from the graphics to the world generation, not forgetting the sound, the addition of biomes, new creatures and more extensive customisation of the settings.

But I can understand that this game isn't for everyone, mainly because it's a god game with no scenario or difficulty, so if that's what you're interested in, it's probably not for you.

The price is also a bit high for what the game is at the moment, I'd go for 10, 12 or even 15 euros, but no more.

One of the game's strong points is that it has a rather active and inventive community, which makes it possible to find interesting worlds or worlds representing specific regions of the world.

I'd say that you shouldn't forget that the game is in beta, but it's progressing at a satisfactory pace, but it's still possible to get bored fairly quickly. Personally, I play the game from time to time when I have a new idea, want to pass the time or when there's a new update.

A word of advice: if you buy the game, type hamburger in the options menu for a while, and you'll have access to a whole range of possibilities.

I would recommend this game to people who play games like Terraria or Minecraft, you play as a deity-like figure who has the power to create/destroy. The game has endless possibilities from having elves fighting orcs, to an apoplectic world where zombies are fighting humans. Overall this game is great to have big stories or recreating worlds, so I would recommend this game to a bunch of people.

Worldbox is a simple to understand game that allows a incredible amount of creativity. This game has become something of a game I play to unwind and relax, cannot recommend enough!

Fair price. Best description I could make would be a Fantasy/Medieval Sandbox Civ Simulator. Its a fun and fairly diverse game that is kind of goofy but not annoyingly random. There are a few aspects that give you a slight realistic sim vibe although it is mostly simplistic. Some moderate to minor complaints: The A.I. can be very stupid. The path finding for units can be very poor (For example on an Earth Map USA could be attacking Russia and they'd load up their soldiers in Alaska then drop them off in Spain to walk all the way across Eurasia). The diplomacy can be very very dumb. I'll use Earth again as an example. Brazil will randomly ally with like Australia which is useless because obviously if a larger country near them declares war on them then Australia isnt going to do shit until the war is already lost. Still a fun game and with mods to add new cool things and to fill in gaps within the game design it can become even better.

Who needs real life when you have Worldbox? I mean, forget about being a productive member of society or paying bills. I've spent 21 hours playing this godforsaken game, and now I'm convinced I'm an actual deity. I go around smiting innocent virtual villagers and creating cataclysmic disasters with a single click. My friends think I've lost it, but little do they know that I've ascended to a higher plane of existence where my powers are limitless. It's hard to say what I like most about this game, because despite being early access, this game is already extremely expansive, and over 9000 more features being planned! However, if I had to choose, I think the Cultures is among my favorite features, with the creature menu and variety of biomes being tied for a close second. I greatly enjoy watching my little world progress. I spend quite a lot of time making maps, often generating random maps several times until I get one that I like, and greatly enjoy watching my little world progress.

I've played iOS for quite a while, almost to completion (and purchased the Premium semi-recently, though even the limited functions available for free still allows for a full experience), but I also bought the desktop version because despite the mobile version being much cheaper than desktop, you miss a lot of the community and modding experience with mobile, especially iOS, due to Apple's "safeguarding" (jail), and the higher processing capacity of computers allows for bigger worlds. I can't find another game that really scratch the same itch as this one, especially within this price range, so if you enjoy Sandbox God Simulations, you will not be disappointed.

"Worldbox" is an astounding game that immerses me in its unique sandbox gameplay. As a player, I am highly satisfied with my experience of this game.

Firstly, the game grants me unlimited creativity and freedom. I can become an all-powerful deity, shaping and controlling an entire world. From terrain and creatures to the development of civilizations, I can mold every detail according to my own will. This freedom of creativity brings me immense joy and satisfaction, with infinite possibilities each time I start the game.

Secondly, the game's simulation system is remarkably well-executed. Creatures and civilizations have their own behaviors and interactions within the game. I can observe the communication between creatures, the growth of civilizations, and the outbreak of wars. This realistic simulation system breathes life into the entire world, where every decision and action has an impact, making me feel like I truly shape an organic ecosystem.

Additionally, the game's graphical style is simple yet charming. While not highly realistic, the game employs a delightful pixel art style that exudes a unique charm. Furthermore, the interface design is intuitive and straightforward, allowing me to easily explore and navigate the game world.

Overall, "Worldbox" allows me to become a mighty creator, shaping a world entirely of my own. The unlimited creativity, engaging simulation system, and captivating graphical style make this game an unforgettable experience. If you enjoy sandbox games and exploring boundless possibilities, I highly recommend "Worldbox" to you, as it will undoubtedly provide endless fun and unleash your creativity.

WorldBox is a unique sandbox simulation game developed by Maxim Karpenko that allows players to become the ultimate deity and shape their own world. With its open-ended gameplay, powerful world-building tools, and limitless creative possibilities, WorldBox offers a relaxing and immersive experience where players can play as a divine architect, molding and observing the lives of their virtual inhabitants.

Endless Creative Freedom:
WorldBox provides players with an incredible amount of creative freedom. As the deity of your own world, you have the power to shape the landscape, control the weather, and create or destroy civilizations. The game's intuitive controls make it easy to place mountains, forests, rivers, and oceans, creating a diverse and visually stunning world.

One of the standout features of WorldBox is the ability to observe and influence the lives of the virtual inhabitants. You can spawn various creatures, including humans, dwarves, elves, and even dragons, and watch as they interact, build settlements, wage wars, and evolve over time. The emergent gameplay and AI-driven behaviors of the inhabitants add depth and unpredictability to each playthrough.

Dynamic and Evolving World:
In WorldBox, the world is constantly changing and evolving. Seasons shift, natural disasters strike, and civilizations rise and fall. The game's simulation mechanics, such as population growth, resource management, and technological progress, create a dynamic and realistic virtual ecosystem. Watching the consequences of your actions unfold in the world you've created is both fascinating and immersive.

The game also includes a variety of special events and challenges that can dramatically impact the world. From epic battles between factions to encounters with mythical creatures, these events add excitement and unpredictability to the gameplay, keeping players engaged and eager to explore new possibilities.

User-friendly Interface and Modding Support:
WorldBox features a user-friendly interface that makes it accessible to players of all skill levels. The intuitive controls and clear tooltips allow for seamless navigation and interaction with the game's mechanics. The game's minimalist art style, accompanied by a soothing soundtrack, adds to the overall relaxing and immersive experience.

Furthermore, WorldBox supports modding, allowing players to extend the game's possibilities even further. The dedicated modding community has created a wealth of user-generated content, including new creatures, items, and gameplay mechanics. This ongoing support and the ability to customize and enhance the game add longevity and replayability.

Conclusion:
WorldBox offers a delightful sandbox experience where players can unleash their creativity and play as the ultimate deity. With its endless creative freedom, dynamic and evolving world, and user-friendly interface, the game provides an immersive and relaxing escape. Whether you enjoy crafting intricate civilizations, observing the lives of your virtual inhabitants, or experimenting with the laws of nature, WorldBox offers a captivating and unique simulation experience that encourages players to let their imagination run wild.

Everything in this game is quite fun and fine, shaping landscapes, creating life... except 3 features i have always wanted to see:

1) to create some "main characters".

By that, i mean the ability to make someone really special and unique, i know there are traits you can give them, buff you can drop on them, but none of that can truly make someone invincible.
Let's say: i want to create a human hero, who is "the protagonist of the story", undefeated in battles, irreplacable part of his faction's strength and its last hope. Currently simply not possible. Being able to freeze and modify a npc's stat would be a solution to this problem. Giving someone HP that never depletes, or insanely high ATK etc...

2) randomness

Have you ever tried using the earthquake to create land and sea? Or used that land ant to create island on an empty ocean? Then you probably noticed that too, the shape and pattern is always the same. The earthquake raised or lowers the terrain by same 2 or 3 fissure shaped forms, do it a few times and you will immediately start to notice it. Put 2 land ants not too far from each other, have them start to create landmass at same time, you will see too, same pattern exactly.

3) god hands use the tile you want it to use
Sometimes i create land using godhands, but it draw terrain i don't want it to create, so half of the time i have to create a god hand, see what it creates, and then pause the game just to kill it again.

From Simple English Wikipedia, the free encyclopedia
Grass is a type of plant with narrow leaves growing from the base. A common kind of grass is used to cover the ground in places such as lawns and parks. Grass is usually the color green. Grasses are monocotyledon herbaceous plants.

The grasses include the "grass" of the family Poaceae. This family is also called Gramineae. The family also include some of the sedges (Cyperaceae) and the rushes (Juncaceae).[1] These three families are not closely related but all of them belong to clades in the order Poales. They are similar adaptations to a common life-style.

The true grasses include cereals, bamboo and the grasses of lawns (turf) and grassland. Uses for graminoids include food (as grain, sprouted grain, shoots or rhizomes), drink (beer, whisky), pasture for livestock, thatching thatch, paper, fuel, clothing, insulation, construction, sports turf, basket weaving and many others.

Many grasses are short, but some grasses can grow tall, such as bamboo. Plants from the grass family can grow in many places and make grasslands, including areas which are very arid or cold. There are several other plants that look similar to grass and are referred to as such, but are not members of the grass family. These plants include rushes, reeds, papyrus and water chestnut. Seagrass is a monocot in the order Alismatales.

Grasses are an important food for many animals, such as deer, buffalo, cattle, mice, grasshoppers, caterpillars and many other grazers. Unlike other plants, grasses grow from the bottom, so when animals eat grass they usually do not destroy the part that grows.[2] This is a part of why the plants are successful. Without grass, soil may wash away into rivers (erosion).

Evolution of grass
Grasses include some of the most versatile plant life-forms. They became widespread toward the end of the Cretaceous. Fossilized dinosaur dung (coprolites) have been found containing grass phytoliths (silica stones inside grass leaves).[3] Grasses have adapted to conditions in lush rain forests, dry deserts, cold mountains and even intertidal habitats, and are now the most widespread plant type. Grass is a valuable source of food and energy for many animals.[4]

Grass and people
Lawn grass is often planted on sports fields and in the area around a building. Sometimes chemicals and water is used to help lawns to grow.

People have used grasses for a long time. People eat parts of grasses. Corn, wheat, barley, oats, rice and millet are cereals, common grains whose seeds are used for food and to make alcohol such as beer.

Sugar comes from sugar cane, which is also a plant in the grass family. People have grown grasses as food for farm animals for about 4,000 years. People use bamboo to build houses, fences, furniture and other things. Grass plants can also be used as fuel, to cover roofs, and to weave baskets.

Language
In English, the word "grass" appears in several phrases. For example:

"The grass is always greener on the other side" means "people are never happy with what they have and want something else".
"Don't let the grass grow under your feet" means "Do something".
"A snake in the grass" is about a person that will not be honest and will trick others.
All flesh is grass: Old Testament book of Isaiah, chapter 40, verses 6–8. A very true observation of the present-day ecology. See the Miocene for the ecological relevance.
Grass is a slang term for cannabis (pot, weed, or marijuana).

Was looking for a nice game I could play with just my mouse while I ingest hard-hitting journalism from the Adam Friedland Show. This is perfect.

Small niche. It hits different from other city-sims that you usually play. Go watch some YouTube footage of gameplay and read up about mods before buying. I find it good but that doesn't mean you would.

How the game works

The game is probably similar to John Connway's game of life. Having simple sets of rules will lead to a difficult to predict and complex outcome.

Main progression system in the game is traits. You farm out traits by inspecting individuals and hovering over the respective traits.

The Good

Breadth of different choices and interactions:
- There are many choices that you can make to affect the entire ecosystem
Chill and relaxing:
- just watch things happen. Great if you're a people observer
Well optimised:
- The game runs very smoothly with large amount of entities and groups executing different actions and making different decisions
Wars are reasonable:
- Countries and races don't start wars without reasons. They usually start it because they need resources. Finite resources lead to war.
Great modding community:
- The modding community puts out high quality mods
High replayability:
- You can sink hours into this game if you can appreciate how things run

The Bad

Awful mod support:
- the game constantly break community mods with mini updates that adds no new content
lack of depth:
- ships don't indicate in their inventory what goods they are transporting. They only seem to show troops being transported. This could potentially mean that ships going in / out of cities to other cities only serves the purpose of visuals, rather than mechanics.
- no proper fresh/salt water systems. Spawn a small number of ppl in desert surrounded by mountains and somehow they can survive without water
- limited technology system. 
  - Your cities improve over time but they don't gain modern weapon or super strong magic. Staffs and small mages from cities exists but they can never be a 1 vs 100.
  - No improved defenses against invading ships, only watch towers with arrows. Where are cannons or magic artillery?
  - No flying ships? 
lack of interaction between God (the player) and cities
- Interaction is always one-way. I do things, they react to the changes. They are unable to communicate with me
- Cities, races and individuals that religious don't pray to me (the god) and ask for wishes or make offerings
lack of minute/micro details:
- Trespassing territories does not incurr hatred / wanting to start war
- cannot configure races to be stronger/weaker
- cannot configure towns/cities to be stronger/weaker
- Disproportionate amount of troops to villagers ratio. There are always around 40% of the population being professional soldiers. This is completely unrealistic. Country leaders being militaristic doesn't affect this ratio and that trait only affects how "war-mongering" they are.

Wonderful game. Many other games in this genre fail in the vein of creativity and freedom, yet you will find little boredom when you recreate the Black Death, whilst forcing humanity to fight a dragon and hundreds of demons. The community is tight-knit and has produced a number of useful, interesting, and simply fun mods. Maps are plentiful, some based on real world areas, others completely original designs.

The base game has a wonderful mix of fantasy details, such as dwarves, orcs, elves (all of which, along with humans, are civilized, meaning they can create countries), and the aforementioned dragons. It also contains many diplomatic and geopolitical features, such as alliances, wars, and more. There is great potential for world building and storytelling through random names and details for tools and weapons, and random cultures that each have a different level of technological development.

10/10, I would love to see what the developers add next.

I think that this game is really fun, but the only reason I would not recommend it is because of the price. On phones, you can get all of the content for around eight dollars, which I think is a fair price. Yet, on steam, the game has a twenty dollar price tag which I just think is too much. Maybe if the game was ten dollars or so I would recommend it, but twenty dollars seems like a lot when I hardly see myself spending twenty hours on this game in a short amount of time, and that is only if you follow the one dollar for one hour of fun rule.

Also, the content does get kind of stale after a while. It was really cool to have god powers at first, but after a couple of play throughs, things start to repeat themselves. Now more often then not I just spend time watching them do their own thing with hardly any interference from me.

World Box - God Simulator offers a tantalizing concept but falls flat in its execution. While its pixelated aesthetic and easy controls are charming, the game's content feels shallow and repetitive, more reminiscent of a mobile game rather than a PC title.

The game's steep price tag doesn't match its value, considering the limited gameplay depth and lack of complexity. It feels like a mobile game ported over to PC, failing to deliver a satisfying, full-fledged god simulation experience.

Until the developers address the content issue and adjust the price, I find it difficult to recommend. Its current state feels more like an overpriced mobile game than a worthy addition to the PC gaming market.

WorldBox is a truly captivating and addictive god simulator and sandbox game that allows players to unleash their creativity and control the fate of an entire world. With its unique concept and extensive range of powers, WorldBox provides an immersive and satisfying experience for both casual and hardcore gamers.

One of the standout features of WorldBox is its impressive level of freedom. As a player, you have the ability to shape the world according to your desires, either by creating a flourishing civilization or by wreaking havoc and destruction upon it. The game provides a wide variety of powers, allowing you to summon natural disasters, control the weather, or even creat mythical creatures. This freedom to experiment and manipulate the world is a major highlight and offers endless possibilities.

The graphics and visuals in WorldBox are simple yet charming. The pixel art style adds a nostalgic touch while still maintaining clarity and readability. The game's user interface is intuitive and easy to navigate, making it accessible to players of all skill levels. The sound design is also well-executed, immersing you in the world you're shaping and enhancing the overall experience.

WorldBox features a comprehensive set of tools and options for world customization. You can shape the terrain, create landscapes, populate the world with different creatures and beings, and establish civilizations with their own cultures and economies. The level of detail and control available is impressive, allowing you to create intricate societies or experiment with different scenarios and challenges.

Additionally, WorldBox benefits from a dedicated and passionate development team that continues to release regular updates and improvements. New features, bug fixes, and optimizations are frequently introduced, ensuring that the game remains fresh and enjoyable over time. The developers also actively engage with the community, taking player feedback into account and incorporating popular suggestions into the game's updates.

While WorldBox offers an incredible experience, it is worth noting that the game is still in development and may have occasional bugs or performance issues. However, the development team has consistently addressed these concerns, demonstrating their commitment to delivering a polished and refined product.

In conclusion, WorldBox is a remarkable god simulator and sandbox game that provides an unparalleled level of freedom and creativity. With its impressive range of powers, extensive customization options, and active development team, WorldBox offers a unique and immersive experience for fans of the genre. Whether you want to build a utopia or unleash chaos, WorldBox is an excellent choice that will keep you entertained for hours on end.

I can spend hours building stuff up, nuke it all in the end, and close out the game happy. Highly recommended.

I strongly advise against purchasing this game due to its lack of content and high price tag. Despite being developed by only one person (or so I've heard), updates and new content are infrequent, making the game feel stagnant and boring after only a short amount of time.

Furthermore, the refund policy is incredibly strict for an early access game. While I understand Steam's refund policy (as you can see from my profile, I am a Steam power user), I strongly believe that it should be less strict for early access games, especially considering that they are not fully developed games. In the case of this particular game, refunds are being rejected even if you've played the game for just above the 2-hour limit. This is unacceptable for an early access game, where bugs and issues are expected.

Additionally, every update breaks most mods, rendering them useless and making it hard to enjoy the game with any added content. It's worth noting that most existing mods have not been updated and many of them are no longer maintained. This is an issue, even in the context of an early access game, and it further limits the replay value of this game.

Given the current state of the game, I cannot recommend it at its current price. A reasonable price point for this game would be around $5 to $7.50. However, even at this lower price, I would advise potential buyers to approach this game with caution and lower expectations, perhaps waiting for the early access to end.

WorldBox - God Simulator is an incredibly engaging and entertaining game that allows players to take on the role of a god and create their own world. The game provides an immense amount of freedom and creativity, as players can manipulate various elements such as terrain, climate, and creatures to build their own civilization.

The graphics and visuals in WorldBox - God Simulator are stunning, with detailed and vivid landscapes, creatures, and weather effects that create a truly immersive experience. The game mechanics are also well-designed, offering a wide range of customization options and settings that make every playthrough unique.

What sets WorldBox - God Simulator apart from other simulation games is its endless possibilities and the ability to create and destroy at will. The game is incredibly addictive and provides hours of entertainment, making it well worth the purchase price.

Overall, I highly recommend WorldBox - God Simulator to anyone looking for a fun and engaging game that offers a unique and immersive experience. The game has received overwhelmingly positive reviews on Steam, and it's easy to see why. With its beautiful graphics, endless possibilities, and addictive gameplay, WorldBox - God Simulator is a must-play for fans of simulation and sandbox games.
